Lab Assignment Five: Wide and Deep Network Architectures¶

Team members: Long Zhang,Qinyu Chen, Zhengwen Zhang

Business understanding¶

Child poverty is the state of children living in poverty, the children may come from very poor families, or orphans living with very limited access to food, water, health care and educations. Child poverty is a serious social problem in the world.

In this lab, we are using a U.S census dataset from Kaggle, the goal of this study is to predict the child poverty rate by evaluating two different deep learning architectures and tuning hyper-parameters for each architecture. We choose this dataset because it has a large dataset for building a wide and deep network. It has a few different categorical features for the creation of the embeddings and cross-product embeddings.This model will be useful for Federal, State or city goverment agencies to take actions to prevent child poverty.

1.2 Identify groups of features in your data that should be combined into cross-product features. Provide justification for why these features should be crossed (or why some features should not be crossed).¶

State:County

The US has 50 states, and each state have different number of counties. For example, in Texas, we have a total of 254 counties. We think the State and County should be crossed, one reason is that different states may have the same county name, for example, "Kings County" is shared among "New York","California" and "Washington" states, we are interested in the different combination of the county and states,so it is necessary to combine these two features.

Transit: Unexployment

This is a particularly interesting pair of features. As is known to all Americans live on the wheel, however, there is huge differences on the Transit style across the US. In big cities like new york city or Boston, the public transport is very convenient, most people will take train or pus regardless or his/her employment status. For those unemployed, he/she may not be able to afford a car, so he/she is most likely to take a Transit instead of driving. in some rural area like west Texas, there is no public transit, people need to drive to everywhere, there may not be a correlation between transit and employment status.

State: Unemployment

As is known to all that there is a large variations for employment rate for different states. for example, Texas's economy has been booming in the past few years, lots of people relocate to Texas for jobs, Some State have been losing people due to deteriorating economy such as detroit in Michigan. so it would be interesting to cross-product the State and unemployment

County:Transit:Unemployment

Again, we combine the three features together because we are interested in the relationship between each other, so County is added to the Transit-Unemployment cross-product.

1.3 Choose and explain what metric(s) you will use to evaluate your algorithm’s performance. You should give a detailed argument for why this (these) metric(s) are appropriate on your data. That is, why is the metric appropriate for the task (e.g., in terms of the business case for the task). Please note: rarely is accuracy the best evaluation metric to use. Think deeply about an appropriate measure of performance.¶

For the evaluation of a model, there are several commonly used metrics, such as precision, recall, accuracy and F1-score, In this lab, we use F1 score as a metric to evaluate the performance of our algorithm, because F1 score allows us to obtain a very realistic measure of our model's performance, it is a harmonic mean of precision and recall, it fives a better measure of the incorrectly classified cases than the accuracy metric. In this model, we would like to predict the poverty level of a child, There are many causes for child poverty, such as parent unemployment, diseases, disabilities,both social and demographic factors can affect child poverty.If we can make a accurate prediction of the child poverty level, the outcome can serve as a guideline for government agencies, NGOs to make appropriate polocies and combat the child poverty. for example, for those extremely poor children, NGOs such as food bank can distribute food directly to those poor children so that they at least have food to survive. for those less poor children, less resources can be allocated to them or to their family. If our model does not make accurate prediction, for example, children from mid-class or wealthy family may not need help at all, resources distributed to them will be a waste and not necessary, using accuracy is not appropriate on our model.compared with Accuracy, F1-score values more on false nagatives and false positive.on the other hand, the features in our model are imbalanced, so F1-score is a better metric to choose.

citation: https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/accuracy-vs-f1-score-6258237beca2

Also,from the confusion matrix, we can find TP is much more than FP, so we use F1 here not accuracy. Accurancy shows terrible when TP>>FP. In order to show confusion matrix, we choose one of confison matrix from modeling part for example.

1.4 Choose the method you will use for dividing your data into training and testing (i.e., are you using Stratified 10-fold cross validation? Shuffle splits? Why?). Explain why your chosen method is appropriate or use more than one method as appropriate. Argue why your cross validation method is a realistic mirroring of how an algorithm would be used in practice.¶

The purpose of cross validation is to keep model stable when sample is not big enough. However, the number of samples is 72718, which is higher than 50000. It is very detailed, so we don't think we need to do cross validation. Also, we do train_validation curve in modeling part, and the curve doesn't overfit.

We only divide our data into train and test. Train takes 80% the whole data, and test takes 20% the whole data. Doing split work here is necessary. Training set is the one on which we train and fit our model basically to fit the parameters whereas test data is used only to assess performance of model. Training data's output is available to model whereas testing data is the unseen data for which predictions have to be made.

In summary, we need to split data, don't need to do cross validation. Here is the example for not overfit.

                 ['Transit','Unemployment'],
                 ['State','Unemployment'],
                 ['County', 'Transit', 'Unemployment']]

we make these three types of crossed columns for three wide and deep network models. 1>first type: we cross state and county together, and then cross Transit and unemployment together. 2>second type: we cross state and county together, and then cross Transit and unemployment together, and then adding state and unemplyment together. 3>third type: we cross state and county together, and then cross Transit and unemployment together, and then crossing state and unemplyment together, and then crossing county and transit and unemployment together.

First wide and deep networks--use cross_column1¶
In [40]:
#Citation From our Notebooks:https://github.com/eclarson/MachineLearningNotebooks/blob/master/10.%20Keras%20Wide%20and%20Deep.ipynb
cross_columns = cross_column1

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
embed_branches = []
X_ints_train = []
X_ints_test = []
all_inputs = []
all_wide_branch_outputs = []

for cols in cross_columns:
    # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
    enc = LabelEncoder()
    
    # create crossed labels
    X_crossed_train = X_df_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
    X_crossed_test = X_df_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
    
    enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
    X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
    X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
    X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
    X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)
    
    # get the number of categories
    N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])
    
    # create embedding branch from the number of categories
    inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
    all_inputs.append(inputs)
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# merge the branches together
wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

# reset this input branch
all_deep_branch_outputs = []
# add in the embeddings
for col in categorical_headers_ints:
    # encode as ints for the embedding
    X_ints_train.append(X_df_train[col].values)
    X_ints_test.append(X_df_test[col].values)
    
    # get the number of categories
    N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])
    
    # create embedding branch from the number of categories
    inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
    all_inputs.append(inputs)
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# also get a dense branch of the numeric features
all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                        sparse=False,
                        name='numeric_data'))

x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

# merge the deep branches together
deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)

From the construction above, we can clearly see the relationship between our layers. Also, input range and output range can also be shown in the constuction. Then we begin to define F1 function, which will be used evaluate your algorithm’s performance.

Precision - Precision is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations.
Precision = TP/TP+FP

Recall (Sensitivity) - Recall is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the all observations in actual class - yes.
Recall = TP/TP+FN

F1 score - F1 Score is the weighted average of Precision and Recall. Therefore, this score takes both false positives and false negatives into account. Intuitively it is not as easy to understand as accuracy, but F1 is usually more useful than accuracy, especially if you have an uneven class distribution. Accuracy works best if false positives and false negatives have similar cost. If the cost of false positives and false negatives are very different, it’s better to look at both Precision and Recall.
F1 Score = 2(Recall Precision) / (Recall + Precision)

Considering F1 score is more comprehesive, we choose F1 score.
Conception cited from:https://blog.exsilio.com/all/accuracy-precision-recall-f1-score-interpretation-of-performance-measures/

In [34]:
from keras import backend as K
def Precision(y_true, y_pred):
    """Precision"""
    tp= K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))  # true positives
    pp= K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_pred, 0, 1))) # predicted positives
    precision = tp/ (pp+ K.epsilon())
    return precision
    
def Recall(y_true, y_pred):
    """Recall"""
    tp = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1))) # true positives
    pp = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1))) # possible positives
    recall = tp / (pp + K.epsilon())
    return recall
def F1(y_true, y_pred):
    """F1-score"""
    precision = Precision(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = Recall(y_true, y_pred)
    f1 = 2 * ((precision * recall) / (precision + recall + K.epsilon()))
    return f1

cross_columns = cross_column2

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
embed_branches = []
X_ints_train = []
X_ints_test = []
all_inputs = []
all_wide_branch_outputs = []

for cols in cross_columns:
    # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
    enc = LabelEncoder()
    
    # create crossed labels
    X_crossed_train = X_df_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
    X_crossed_test = X_df_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
    
    enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
    X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
    X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
    X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
    X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)
    
    # get the number of categories
    N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])
    
    # create embedding branch from the number of categories
    inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
    all_inputs.append(inputs)
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# merge the branches together
wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

# reset this input branch
all_deep_branch_outputs = []
# add in the embeddings
for col in categorical_headers_ints:
    # encode as ints for the embedding
    X_ints_train.append(X_df_train[col].values)
    X_ints_test.append(X_df_test[col].values)
    
    # get the number of categories
    N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])
    
    # create embedding branch from the number of categories
    inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
    all_inputs.append(inputs)
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# also get a dense branch of the numeric features
all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                        sparse=False,
                        name='numeric_data'))

x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

# merge the deep branches together
deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)

deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)

2.2 Investigate generalization performance by altering the number of layers in the deep branch of the network. Try at least two different number of layers. Use the method of cross validation and evaluation metric that you argued for at the beginning of the lab to select the number of layers that performs superiorly.¶

After searching on google, we find some rule about choose number of hidden layer(cite from:https://www.heatonresearch.com/2017/06/01/hidden-layers.html):

The number of hidden neurons should be between the size of the input layer and the size of the output layer.
The number of hidden neurons should be 2/3 the size of the input layer, plus the size of the output layer.
The number of hidden neurons should be less than twice the size of the input layer
Considering about running time, we choose 5 10 20 40 80...

In [51]:
def AlterLayer_network(layers=[]):
    cross_columns = cross_column1

    # we need to create separate lists for each branch
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_wide_branch_outputs = []

    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        # create crossed labels
        X_crossed_train = X_df_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_df_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
        X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # merge the branches together
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []
    # add in the embeddings
    for col in categorical_headers_ints:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        X_ints_train.append(X_df_train[col].values)
        X_ints_test.append(X_df_test[col].values)

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # also get a dense branch of the numeric features
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                            sparse=False,
                            name='numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    for idx, layer in enumerate(layers):
        deep_branch = Dense(units=layer,activation='relu', name='deep{}'.format(str(idx+1)))(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)
    model.compile(optimizer='adagrad',
                  loss='mean_squared_error',
                  metrics=[F1,'accuracy'])
    
    X_train = X_ints_train+ [X_train_num]
    X_test = X_ints_test + [X_test_num]
    
    return model, X_train, X_test

def wide_deep_network1(layers=[]):
    cross_columns = cross_column1

    # we need to create separate lists for each branch
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_wide_branch_outputs = []

    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        # create crossed labels
        X_crossed_train = X_df_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_df_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
        X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # merge the branches together
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []
    # add in the embeddings
    for col in categorical_headers_ints:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        X_ints_train.append(X_df_train[col].values)
        X_ints_test.append(X_df_test[col].values)

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # also get a dense branch of the numeric features
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                            sparse=False,
                            name='numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    for idx, layer in enumerate(layers):
        deep_branch = Dense(units=layer,activation='relu', name='deep{}'.format(str(idx+1)))(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)
    model.compile(optimizer='adagrad',
                  loss='mean_squared_error',
                  metrics=[F1])
    
    X_train = X_ints_train+ [X_train_num]
    X_test = X_ints_test + [X_test_num]
    return model, X_train, X_test
